Virgil’s line (Aen. vi. 603), “Lucent ge- nialibus altis flul-ea fulcra toris,’' which is usually quoted in this place, does not refer to the marriage-bed, but to banquets in honour of the genii, such as the Romans celebrated on their birthdays and at other times. (C. iii. 17. 14.) The bed was a symbol of domestic love and peace, and was placed where it was for a omen.
